{
  "doc_id": "16256",
  "text": "It is of note that, though PostC affects structural features of mitochondria, it does not influence mitochondrial respiration [CITATION_1] . In particular, in mitochondria isolated from PostC hearts basal state 4 or ADP-stimulated state 3 respirations are not affected, thus excluding uncoupling or inhibition of the respiratory chain as a mechanism of mPTP inhibition [CITATION_2] . Nevertheless, while basal respiration was not affected, ADP-stimulated respiration was increased after pharmacological PostC with morphine [CITATION_3] . This last observation is in line with many reports showing that a mild degree of mitochondrial dysfunction confers protection against I/R injury [CITATION_4] . It is also in line with the important role of mitochondrial Cx43 for oxygen consumption and ATP production. In fact inhibition or reduction of mitochondrial Cx43 specifically decreases complex I respiration [CITATION_5] . Mitochondrial Cx43 is important for both ROS signaling and respiration in cardiac conditioning.",
